passages.text: Investor Day '25: Maintain 27 guidance in US\$ terms should be positive for the stock

ASM International hosts its Investor Day on Sept \(23^{\mathrm{rd}}\) . We think it well expected that the company will adjust 2027 guidance to indicate it was given in US\$ terms. If adjusted for the current \(\epsilon /\mathbb{S}\) , the company's '27 guidance equates to revenue of \(\epsilon 3.7\mathrm{bn - 4.6bn}\) . Current Bloomberg expectations are now \(1.1\%\) below the mid- point of this range, thus we do not believe that there a significant risk from the company adjusting guidance. This adjusted guidance would imply a roughly \(12\%\) revenue CAGR from '25- '27. With the share gains associated with GAA continuing, we we think the underlying US\$ guidance is unlikely to be adjusted. We also expect the company to give '30 guidance at the investor day. With the stock down for the year and also down from late- spring highs, we believe that re- iterating the '27 guidance should help the stock. We maintain our Overweight rating.

2027 guidance likely to be adjusted to be at constant currency, but that will not be a surprise: ASM International guided to '27 revenue of \(\epsilon 4\mathrm{bn - 5bn}\) When this guidance was provided in Sept '23, the \(\epsilon /\mathbb{S}\) was at 1.05- 1.07. With the \(\epsilon /\mathbb{S}\) now at 1.16- 1.17, it seems fairly obvious that the company will fairly that the guidance was given at the Sept '23 exchange rate. At the current exchange rate, that guidance would be equivalent to \(\epsilon 3.7\mathrm{bn - 4.6bn}\) or \(\epsilon 4.15\mathrm{bn}\) at the mid- point. Current BBG consensus for the company in '27 is for revenue of \(\epsilon 4.1\mathrm{bn}\) which is \(1.1\%\) below the mid- point of this adjusted guidance. With the investor base negative, we think that maintaining '27 guidance (given in '23) at the same level in US\$ terms would be positive for the stock.

China demand linearity remains uncertain: ASM International and some of its semi- cap peers have indicated that they have seen weakening in China- related shipments in 2H25. China was a large percentage of sales in '24 (exact percentage not disclosed) and is indicated to be in the high \(20\%\) of sales in '25. The market expects China sales will decline in '26 to the low \(20\%\) range. If the decline is only to \(\sim 20\%\) then it is unlikely to be negative for the company; if the decline is more than that, then the question is whether it is likely to have an impact on '27 guidance.

Market share is coming up in multiple conversations with investors and the company will need to address it or else it will remain an overhang: ASM International is the leader in the ALD market and a key player in the semiconductordustry transition to Gate All Around (GAA) technology. The GAA transition is proceeding well in the logic space, but investor attention seems to have moved to the shift to molybdenum (Moly) in the metal layers. ASMIdid not have any market share in the metallization space ahead of the Moly transition and thus any wins they have there would be incremental. Investor concerns are about their overall Atomic layer deposition share (Moly is deposited using ALD) and thus the company needs to guide the market regarding this share going forward and whether management expect it to remain in the \(55\% +\) range guided previously, given the use of ALD in new markets.

ASM International has significantly improved its position in the semi- cap industry in the past couple of years. All major leading edge semi manufacturers have begun to use its ALD tools for 5mn/3nm/2nm processes. It dominates the logic market in ALD. Its position in the memory market is improving. In particular, as DRAM uses logic like high- k metal gates and then moves to 4F2 architecture, it will use more single wafer ALD tools, benefiting ASMI. ASMI has also increased its share in Epitaxy over the last four years, expanding its share well beyond its historical customer/s.

Since moving to a high growth mode enabled by ALD, ASM shares have traded at a P/E of 20- 40x. 2025 marks the onset of 2nm mass production and ALD intensive deposition structures in semiconductors. However, current macro uncertainties suggest ASMI should trade at a discount to the midpoint of this valuation range. We estimates that ASM's stock should trade at \(\sim 27.5x\) on '27e EPS, which would be equivalent to €624. We discount this for one year (given our PT horizon of end- date of Dec '26) using a \(9\%\) discount rate which would give the company a share price target of €573. Apart from this, the company owns \(25\%\) of ASM Pacific with a current market value of €14 per share. Putting it all together results in our Dec- 26 price target for the stock of €587.

ASM International guided at its 2023 Investor Day that it would achieve €4bn- 5bn of revenue in 2027. This guidance was proffered when the € was at \(1.05 - 1.07\) or an average of about \(1.06\) . The US dollar is now \(- 9.5\%\) weaker. Some \(80\%\) of ASM International's revenue is in US dollars. Thus the '27 guidance is now equivalent to - €3.7bn- 4.6bn at the new exchange rate. At the mid- point of this guidance, ASM International would need to achieve €4.15bn of sales in '27. Current Bloomberg consensus expects the company to achieve €4.1bn, which implies revenue increasing at a 2- year CAGR of \(11.9\%\) from the €3.27bn expected in '25. Given that consensus estimates have already been reduced to below the mid- point of the guidance ASM International gave in Sept '23, the risk of the company lowering the guidance is low, in our opinion, given it will continue to benefit from the rollout of GAA.

Based on Gartner data for 2024, ASM International's Atomic layer deposition (ALD) market share improved in '24 from its '22 low and the size of the ALD market increased by \(11.6\%\) in the year, faster than WFE growth of \(8.6\%\) . Gartner data also indicates that ASM International grew its ALD revenue by \(33\%\) in the year, substantially faster than ALD market growth and more than 4x WFE growth. The key to the stock, however, is how the company's ALD share will develop in '26, '27 as Molybdenum deposition using ALD becomes a bigger percentage of the ALD market.
Figure 1: ALD market share
Applied Materials at its August 3Q25 conference call said: "...we also secured our first win in moly deposition for the most critical device performance applications".

Lam Research, at its July \(30^{\text{th}}\) 4Q 25 conference call said: "Our Halo ALD moly tool, [...] is ramping at multiple NAND customers this year. We expect moly adoption to increase broadly as more customers convert NAND capacity to 200 layers and higher in the next few years. LAM is leading the industry transition to ALD moly not only in NAND, but also in foundry logic. AI is driving greater transistor performance requirements and, in turn, accelerating the inflection to gate- all- around device

architectures. However, below 2 nanometers, gate- all- around structures begin to encounter significant resistance capacitance, or RC, challenges. Narrower transistor contacts in these devices cause greater electron scattering, resulting in higher resistance of the deposited tungsten films.

"Replacing tungsten with molybdenum solves the resistance problem, but the process of depositing this higher- performance material is inherently slower and more complex. This is driving a roughly 3x increase in LAM metal deposition SAM per wafer when transitioning to advanced gate- all- around nodes. Today, we are the only company with ALD moly tools already in production in foundry logic and, in the June quarter, we secured a key win at another leading foundry customer for their next- generation application.

"As Moly adoption expands across various metal interconnect layers, the flexibility of Lam's unique multi- station architecture to execute both plasma and thermal processing in the same chamber, enables optimization of process conditions and process step sequencing to meet requirements for different applications and over multiple generations of future logic devices."
ASM International said at its July 25 conference call: "We've said that a few times that we have some wins in Moly in logic/foundry and already have shipped some tools."

ASM International has strong market share in Gate All Around (GAA) with all the major semiconductor manufacturers. Metal is a new market that the company is entering because Molybdenum (Moly) requires ALD to deposit it rather than the previously used PVD/CVD. Thus, its leadership in ALD has allowed ASM to enter a new market. However, the pre- Moly metal deposition market is dominated by Applied Materials and Lam Research. Thus the key question is what ASM's share in the Moly market will be as this will likely have implications for ASM International's ALD market share.

Epitaxy: Slowdown in power and analog market where ASM has considerable share has likely impacted shareGartner data shows that ASM International lost share in the Epitaxy market in '24. This could be the result of a slowdown in the power and analog market where ASM's historical market share in Epitaxy has been. At the same time, the company is growing share in the leading edge, due to GAA. If the data is correct, it would indicate a very substantial decline in the power and analog market because the data also indicates significant share gains in ALD and the share gains of ASM in Epitaxy are related to the growth of ALD with GAA. Thus, ASM International will need to explain whether its expected share gains in Epitaxy in the leading edge have had issues or if the data is essentially indicating a significant decline in the power and analog market, which has impacted ASM's share due to the company's strong position in that market segment.
